  <span id="freeText12145964482978012871" style="display:none">The attraction of this book to me is that it is a 'sequel' to "The Godfather". I knew what I was getting into when I started it. It's pretty clear from any description of it that it's not really a sequel to "The Godfather". <br /><br />Yes, Michael Corleone is in it, before he left Sicily after his exile. Even Clemenza and Don Vito Corleone make appearances. But most of this book is about completely different characters, and the ones we know from "The Godfather" are merely making cameos. (I never saw the film version of this book, but apparently a deal was struck to avoid litigation to leave any references to "The Godfather" characters out. Maybe one day I'll see the film.)<br /><br />For the most part, I found this book uninteresting and slow. I wanted more of Michael Corleone, more information about what he did before he left Sicily. It took me a long time to finish this because I kept getting distracted by other books I wanted to read and then I would come back, determined to finish it.</span>
