  <span id="freeText919908710573119001" style="display:none">'The Sicilian' is the sequel to the cult classic 'The Godfather' and chronicles the times of Michael Corleone's exile in Sicily . The novel is based on the real life exploits of Salvatore "Turi" Giuliano (spelling was intentionally changed in the novel ) . <br /><br />The best things I found about this book is that the situations of transformation of "lad Turi" to "bandit Turi" are still relevant . There are numerous stories throughout our nation same as Turi's . The second best thing about the book is its character building . Each and every character is used very intelligently by the author . <br /><br />The plot of the book lacked the enigma which its prequel had . The book was more biographical then fiction . In many places the situations are stratched by uselessly describing the personality of the protagonist and it is repeated again and again throughout the novel . The plot is plain with completely predictable twists . The dialogues were nowhere near the great dialogues of the prequel . <br /><br />Overall a good read . Not as great as "The Godfather" .<br /><br />3.5 Stars .</span>
